1
00:00:24,111 --> 00:00:28,724
[clock ticking]

2
00:00:31,074 --> 00:00:31,727
[typing]

3
00:00:34,512 --> 00:00:37,602
[man] We are going through
the most profound change

4
00:00:37,689 --> 00:00:41,302
in communication technologies
in all of human history
right now.

5
00:00:43,304 --> 00:00:45,828
[chattering]

6
00:00:45,915 --> 00:00:50,441
Printing press,
radio, telegraph, television.
All very important.

7
00:00:50,528 --> 00:00:54,228
But I believe we're going
through the most transformative,

8
00:00:54,315 --> 00:00:57,579
purely on the basis
of three technologies.

9
00:00:57,666 --> 00:01:00,669
Mobile, social media
and cloud computing.

10
00:01:07,937 --> 00:01:10,505
They share one
very important characteristic.

11
00:01:10,592 --> 00:01:14,291
And that's the amount
of private information.

12
00:01:14,378 --> 00:01:17,903
Information that used to
be in our desktops
or filing cabinets,

13
00:01:17,990 --> 00:01:19,514
even in our heads,

14
00:01:19,601 --> 00:01:22,430
that we now
entrust to third parties.

15
00:01:22,517 --> 00:01:24,910
[whirring]

16
00:01:24,997 --> 00:01:28,653
Data that we are conscious of,
and deliberate about,

17
00:01:28,740 --> 00:01:31,743
like the e-mails we send
and the tweets we post.

18
00:01:31,830 --> 00:01:34,398
But it also includes
a lot of information

19
00:01:34,485 --> 00:01:37,358
that we're completely,
or mostly, unconscious about.

20
00:01:38,663 --> 00:01:40,622
So if you take my mobile phone,

21
00:01:40,709 --> 00:01:44,060
even when I'm not using it,
it's emitting a pulse,

22
00:01:44,147 --> 00:01:47,846
trying to locate
the nearest Wi-Fi router
or cell phone exchange,

23
00:01:47,933 --> 00:01:50,719
and within that beacon is
the make and model of the phone,

24
00:01:51,763 --> 00:01:53,461
the fact that it's my phone,

25
00:01:53,548 --> 00:01:56,507
because my name is attached
to the operating system,

26
00:01:56,594 --> 00:01:59,423
and most importantly,
the geolocation of the phone.

27
00:01:59,510 --> 00:02:02,557
[drone humming]

28
00:02:02,644 --> 00:02:04,385
[man speaking Portuguese]

29
00:02:10,086 --> 00:02:12,915
[Deibert continues]
We are leaving
this digital exhaust

30
00:02:13,002 --> 00:02:17,876
that contains
extraordinarily precise
information about our lives,

31
00:02:17,963 --> 00:02:22,446
our social relationships
reduced to
trillions of data points

32
00:02:22,533 --> 00:02:27,234
that form now
this new ethereal layer
around the planet

33
00:02:27,321 --> 00:02:29,845
that's only growing
in all directions.

34
00:02:29,932 --> 00:02:34,719
[ticking]

35
00:02:34,806 --> 00:02:38,419
Capabilities are being put
in the hands of policy makers,

36
00:02:38,506 --> 00:02:42,162
five years ago,
they'd never imagine
that they would have.

37
00:02:42,249 --> 00:02:45,991
This is where big
data meets Big Brother.

38
00:02:46,905 --> 00:02:50,257
[ticking]

39
00:02:56,524 --> 00:03:00,832
[buzzing]

40
00:03:04,836 --> 00:03:07,274
-[folk music]
-[chuckles]

41
00:03:07,361 --> 00:03:08,318
[man with accent]
Should be here.

42
00:03:10,625 --> 00:03:12,540
[American man]
It is kind of in a rock,
I think.

43
00:03:12,627 --> 00:03:14,498
[American man #2]
Yeah, the entrance is in a rock.

44
00:03:14,585 --> 00:03:16,500
-[speaking over each other]
-Or a bunker.

45
00:03:16,587 --> 00:03:18,546
Oh, yeah, the bunker.
It is down there!

46
00:03:21,897 --> 00:03:23,507
[driver]
There is a bunker
under here.

47
00:03:23,594 --> 00:03:27,032
-[man] Yeah.
-It is between 33 and 39.

48
00:03:27,119 --> 00:03:28,338
[Deibert] Right there.
Look at that door.

49
00:03:28,425 --> 00:03:29,600
[driver] Yeah.[Deibert] Yeah, this is it.

50
00:03:29,687 --> 00:03:31,559
Bahnhof.[driver] Okay.

51
00:03:42,265 --> 00:03:43,527
[beeps]

52
00:03:54,016 --> 00:03:55,844
[door squeaks]Hey, I guess we just go in.

53
00:04:00,849 --> 00:04:04,592
[electronica music]

54
00:04:16,038 --> 00:04:19,520
[servers whirring]

55
00:04:21,391 --> 00:04:24,525
[electronica continues]

56
00:04:26,788 --> 00:04:28,790
What's your favorite
part of the building?

57
00:04:28,877 --> 00:04:30,835
I think it's here.
I mean, I love it.

58
00:04:30,922 --> 00:04:33,316
Yeah.[loud whirring]

59
00:04:33,403 --> 00:04:35,797
All the energy down here.
The noise and stuff
like that.

60
00:04:35,884 --> 00:04:38,495
It's kind of a...It's like being in a hive.

61
00:04:38,582 --> 00:04:39,583
Yeah.Yeah, exactly.

62
00:04:55,730 --> 00:05:00,256
Many people believe that
you have this cloud services
that are floating around.

63
00:05:00,343 --> 00:05:02,519
People think, "Okay,
it's a cloud server."

64
00:05:02,606 --> 00:05:06,044
But this is
the actual physical location
of the Internet.

65
00:05:06,131 --> 00:05:09,004
[whirring, clicking]

66
00:05:14,488 --> 00:05:17,795
[Karlung continues]
It's a constant struggle
to protect data.

67
00:05:17,882 --> 00:05:22,322
[voices echo]

68
00:05:22,409 --> 00:05:26,674
The Swedish Security Police
wanted to install tools

69
00:05:26,761 --> 00:05:32,027
to automatically
log in to our data
and get out the information.

70
00:05:33,202 --> 00:05:35,204
So I invited them
to our facility,

71
00:05:35,291 --> 00:05:37,511
and then I had a microphone

72
00:05:37,598 --> 00:05:42,777
which I was provided
by the Swedish Public Service,
national radio.

73
00:05:46,737 --> 00:05:51,568
[speaking Swedish]

74
00:05:57,313 --> 00:06:00,447
I taped this conversation,
and they were so angry.

75
00:06:00,534 --> 00:06:03,493
And they also wanted us
to sign a paper

76
00:06:03,580 --> 00:06:06,975
where they said that
we could not say
anything about it.

77
00:06:07,062 --> 00:06:08,933
It should be total secrecy.

78
00:06:09,020 --> 00:06:13,373
They said,
"If a terrorist attack happens,
it's your fault."

79
00:06:13,460 --> 00:06:14,765
[click, buzz]

80
00:06:14,852 --> 00:06:20,641
[man speaks Swedish]

81
00:06:28,300 --> 00:06:30,564
[Karlung]
It's, like, a creepy feeling.

82
00:06:30,651 --> 00:06:34,219
Nobody can say that
any facility is safe.

83
00:06:34,306 --> 00:06:39,181
There are always possibilities
to go in and find data
and take it out.

84
00:06:42,793 --> 00:06:46,275
People say that,
"Oh, I don't have
anything to hide.

85
00:06:46,362 --> 00:06:48,059
They can read my mail.
I don't have anything."

86
00:06:48,146 --> 00:06:51,193
But it's not that
which is this problem.

87
00:06:51,280 --> 00:06:55,676
The problem is, without secrecy,
there can be no democracy.

88
00:06:55,763 --> 00:06:58,505
Without secrecy,
there can be no market economy.

89
00:06:59,331 --> 00:07:00,855
Right.

90
00:07:00,942 --> 00:07:03,597
There is an obvious candidate
for the Nobel Peace Prize.

91
00:07:03,684 --> 00:07:06,034
Really?And that is Edward Snowden.

92
00:07:06,121 --> 00:07:07,514
I mean, yeah.

93
00:07:21,571 --> 00:07:28,186
Does the public enjoy
the same right to privacy
that we have in the past?

94
00:07:28,273 --> 00:07:30,972
Are we still private citizens,

95
00:07:31,059 --> 00:07:34,584
and then public officials,
where the government knows
very little about us,

96
00:07:34,671 --> 00:07:36,107
but we know
everything about them?

97
00:07:36,194 --> 00:07:39,197
Why are we, the public,
becoming disempowered

98
00:07:39,284 --> 00:07:42,026
at the same time
that governments
around the world,

99
00:07:42,113 --> 00:07:47,336
corporations around the world,
institutions around the world,

100
00:07:47,423 --> 00:07:52,210
are gaining greater
and greater leverage over
the range of our activities,

101
00:07:52,297 --> 00:07:54,430
their knowledge of what we do?

102
00:08:08,139 --> 00:08:10,228
[Deibert] The Citizen Lab
is an unusual place.

103
00:08:10,315 --> 00:08:13,449
[cell phones ringing]

104
00:08:13,536 --> 00:08:16,583
We're a research unit
at the University of Toronto.

105
00:08:18,846 --> 00:08:22,371
We combine the skills
of engineers,
computer scientists

106
00:08:22,458 --> 00:08:24,155
with social scientists.

107
00:08:24,242 --> 00:08:26,810
We collaborate with people
from all over the world

108
00:08:26,897 --> 00:08:29,073
to do the field research
that we do.

109
00:08:29,160 --> 00:08:32,512
And we do this
to advance research
on global security,

110
00:08:32,599 --> 00:08:34,514
cyberspace
and human rights.

111
00:08:37,386 --> 00:08:39,214
The world is
a very dangerous place

112
00:08:39,301 --> 00:08:42,522
as we saw recently in...
in tragic incidents
in Paris,

113
00:08:42,609 --> 00:08:47,265
and you want to
have security agencies
be well adept at discerning

114
00:08:47,352 --> 00:08:49,703
what those threats
are over our horizon.

115
00:08:49,790 --> 00:08:55,099
But is it okay
that the government sets up
a giant digital X-ray machine

116
00:08:55,186 --> 00:08:56,971
over everything that we do?

117
00:08:57,058 --> 00:08:59,147
Because that's effectively
where we're headed right now.

118
00:08:59,234 --> 00:09:00,540
[typing]

119
00:09:02,716 --> 00:09:05,762
[continues]
We've been a kind of
digital early warning system,

120
00:09:05,849 --> 00:09:07,982
scanning the horizon.

121
00:09:08,069 --> 00:09:10,898
And what we've seen, frankly,
has been really disturbing.

122
00:09:10,985 --> 00:09:13,161
[digital chirping]

123
00:09:14,771 --> 00:09:16,338
[typing]

124
00:09:23,214 --> 00:09:26,130
[praying, chanting]

125
00:09:30,961 --> 00:09:33,007
[chanting in Tibetan]

126
00:09:37,185 --> 00:09:39,796
[man, in Tibetan]
It was around 4:30.
We had just finished praying.

127
00:09:43,974 --> 00:09:49,197
Sixty or 70 police arrived along
with 300 or 400 soldiers.

128
00:09:51,155 --> 00:09:52,940
They forced their
way into the monastery.

129
00:10:01,078 --> 00:10:03,559
[chimes playing]

130
00:10:15,571 --> 00:10:19,488
[Golog, in Tibetan]
They started ransacking
the monastery.

131
00:10:19,575 --> 00:10:23,797
All the monks were asking,
"Why are they here?
What are they doing here?"

132
00:10:23,884 --> 00:10:26,626
Everyone was nervous.
I had a sinking feeling.

133
00:10:26,713 --> 00:10:30,107
One of the monastery's artists
was arguing with the police,
and I tried to intercede.

134
00:10:30,194 --> 00:10:33,545
Suddenly my phone rang,
so I quickly switched it off.

135
00:10:33,633 --> 00:10:36,897
I switched off my phone.

136
00:10:43,555 --> 00:10:47,472
We could hear the police outside
talking in Chinese
on walkie-talkies.

137
00:10:47,559 --> 00:10:49,910
Then the police searching inside
were called out.

138
00:10:51,476 --> 00:10:53,957
I could see one of them
looking closely at a photo.

139
00:10:54,044 --> 00:10:56,307
But I couldn't see
if it was a photo of me or not.

140
00:10:56,394 --> 00:11:00,224
Then they came back in
and pointed a gun
to each of our heads,

141
00:11:00,311 --> 00:11:04,359
and we were told to put
our phones down on the ground
in front of them...

142
00:11:05,534 --> 00:11:08,580
as they kept us all at gunpoint.

143
00:11:08,668 --> 00:11:14,630
So I switched my phone back on

144
00:11:14,717 --> 00:11:17,981
and put it down
in front of them.

145
00:11:23,421 --> 00:11:28,557
[vibrates]

146
00:11:28,644 --> 00:11:30,994
Just after I switched it
back on, my phone rang.

147
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:39,394
The police asked, "Whose phone
is this?" I said, "It's mine."

148
00:11:40,787 --> 00:11:45,182
-[shouts]
-[blows landing]

149
00:11:45,269 --> 00:11:47,619
They started beating me
with their rifles,

150
00:11:47,707 --> 00:11:49,796
striking me with the points
and the butts of their guns.

151
00:11:52,059 --> 00:11:55,018
-[shouting in Tibetan]
-[blows landing]

152
00:11:55,105 --> 00:11:57,412
Then a bunch of them grabbed me,
and dragged me away.

153
00:11:59,849 --> 00:12:02,722
[beating continues]

154
00:12:04,767 --> 00:12:09,685
[stops]

155
00:12:13,167 --> 00:12:19,695
[Golog]
They had complete records
of all our phone conversations.

156
00:12:20,696 --> 00:12:23,743
They knew everything.

157
00:12:23,830 --> 00:12:27,703
[vehicle horns honking]

158
00:12:33,840 --> 00:12:37,495
[woman, in English]
Tibetans are watched from every
angle and from every corner.

159
00:12:37,582 --> 00:12:41,282
It's in their homes,
it's in their offices,
it's in the streets.

160
00:12:41,369 --> 00:12:43,240
In Tibet,
certainly in central Tibet

161
00:12:43,327 --> 00:12:45,765
and around
the capital city of Lhasa,

162
00:12:45,852 --> 00:12:49,246
Chinese authorities,
together with
Chinese corporations,

163
00:12:49,333 --> 00:12:51,509
telecommunications companies,

164
00:12:51,596 --> 00:12:56,210
they've integrated
the ability to spy on people
via their mobile phone,

165
00:12:56,297 --> 00:12:59,213
via the last communications they
may have had over the Internet.

166
00:12:59,300 --> 00:13:02,477
Down to the closed circuit
television camera
on the streets.

167
00:13:04,131 --> 00:13:07,134
The Chinese so strictly
control access to Tibet,

168
00:13:07,221 --> 00:13:09,092
it's just like a black hole

169
00:13:09,179 --> 00:13:12,400
for media,
for independent observers,

170
00:13:12,487 --> 00:13:14,097
for international agencies,
for anything.

171
00:13:21,017 --> 00:13:23,454
[Golog, in Tibetan]
Ever since I started being
politically active,

172
00:13:23,541 --> 00:13:27,589
I never gave a thought
to my own security.

173
00:13:27,676 --> 00:13:33,421
I just see it
as a responsibility
that comes with being Tibetan.

174
00:13:40,950 --> 00:13:42,909
[woman speaks in Tibetan]

175
00:13:44,388 --> 00:13:49,089
[Golog]
How I escaped is a secret.

176
00:13:49,176 --> 00:13:51,091
[light music]

177
00:14:07,977 --> 00:14:10,371
[Tethong]
People
are incredibly courageous.

178
00:14:10,458 --> 00:14:13,635
People inside Tibet will
send out news and information.

179
00:14:13,722 --> 00:14:16,681
And they'll say,
"I want this story to be told."

180
00:14:17,813 --> 00:14:19,119
They could be imprisoned.

181
00:14:19,206 --> 00:14:20,598
They could be tortured.

182
00:14:20,685 --> 00:14:22,209
Their family
could pay the price.

183
00:14:22,296 --> 00:14:23,558
[music continues]

184
00:14:23,645 --> 00:14:25,777
We on the outside have to decide

185
00:14:25,865 --> 00:14:31,348
how to walk this very,
sort of, fine line between
protecting people's security

186
00:14:31,435 --> 00:14:35,048
and honoring their wishes
about getting news
and information out.

187
00:14:35,135 --> 00:14:39,530
And we know for a fact,
thanks to Citizen Lab's report,

188
00:14:39,617 --> 00:14:42,620
that we are being
successfully targeted.

189
00:14:42,707 --> 00:14:44,666
[music stops]

190
00:14:44,753 --> 00:14:49,236
A new report has been released
from a group
of digital detectives.

191
00:14:49,323 --> 00:14:53,153
From their computers in Toronto,
they've tracked
a high-tech spy ring

192
00:14:53,240 --> 00:14:54,545
that reaches around the world.

193
00:14:55,372 --> 00:14:57,505
[typewriter clicks]

194
00:14:59,246 --> 00:15:00,638
[reporter] For the past ten months,

195
00:15:00,725 --> 00:15:03,728
these computer experts have been working as cyber sleuths

196
00:15:03,815 --> 00:15:07,036
hot on the trail of a massive electronic spy network.

197
00:15:07,123 --> 00:15:11,388
They say it has taken control of nearly 1,300 high-level computers

198
00:15:11,475 --> 00:15:13,608
in more than 100 countries.

199
00:15:13,695 --> 00:15:17,133
A discovery that could have major political implications.

200
00:15:17,220 --> 00:15:19,788
They can extract any
document they wanted.

201
00:15:19,875 --> 00:15:23,748
They could turn on web cameras,
turn on audio devices,

202
00:15:23,835 --> 00:15:25,794
so that they could,
in effect, use the computers

203
00:15:25,881 --> 00:15:27,839
as a listening device
in the offices.

204
00:15:27,927 --> 00:15:30,494
[reporter] The web of intrigue started with the Dalai Lama

205
00:15:30,581 --> 00:15:32,279
who thought his computer had been hacked.

206
00:15:36,631 --> 00:15:41,244
Up until about 2007 or 2008,
I'd never really heard
of malware.

207
00:15:41,331 --> 00:15:43,681
You know, I'd heard
of viruses, obviously,

208
00:15:43,768 --> 00:15:46,641
but I hadn't really heard
about targeted malware attacks

209
00:15:46,728 --> 00:15:48,251
affecting
the human rights community.

210
00:15:48,338 --> 00:15:49,557
[clicking]

211
00:15:53,822 --> 00:15:57,130
First time I heard about it was
in the context of the Tibetans.

212
00:15:57,217 --> 00:16:01,699
Gradually
we started piecing together,
they are under surveillance.

213
00:16:01,786 --> 00:16:05,877
The surveillance comes
from groups within China.

214
00:16:05,965 --> 00:16:10,970
They're using malicious software
and socially-engineered e-mails.

215
00:16:11,057 --> 00:16:13,581
E-mails that are crafted
to get them to open it up

216
00:16:13,668 --> 00:16:15,409
to get inside their devices.

217
00:16:16,932 --> 00:16:18,978
[reporter] Nart Villeneuve, a computer wiz,

218
00:16:19,065 --> 00:16:21,197
figured out how the operation worked

219
00:16:21,284 --> 00:16:24,026
by getting the attackers to hack into his computer.

220
00:16:24,113 --> 00:16:25,723
We're monitoring these groups

221
00:16:25,810 --> 00:16:27,943
for long periods of time,

222
00:16:28,030 --> 00:16:30,859
and you're essentially waiting
for them to screw up, right?

223
00:16:30,946 --> 00:16:32,904
And when they do,
you take advantage of that.

224
00:16:32,992 --> 00:16:35,081
Sometimes it takes a long time.

225
00:16:35,168 --> 00:16:38,127
You could be monitoring a group
for a year and get nothing.

226
00:16:38,214 --> 00:16:42,697
Then one day,
they just use a server
that they don't lock down

227
00:16:42,784 --> 00:16:44,438
and all the data's
just sitting there.

228
00:16:46,396 --> 00:16:48,964
I was at home.
It was pretty late.

229
00:16:49,660 --> 00:16:51,575
[typing]

230
00:17:20,387 --> 00:17:21,823
[Deibert]
Nart was scouring through it,

231
00:17:21,910 --> 00:17:24,565
trying to figure out
what actor is responsible

232
00:17:24,652 --> 00:17:26,828
for getting inside
the Dalai Lama's office.

233
00:17:26,915 --> 00:17:30,919
And there was
a 22 or 24 character string
that kept coming up

234
00:17:31,006 --> 00:17:33,574
that he couldn't figure out,
"What is the meaning of this?"

235
00:17:33,661 --> 00:17:37,926
So on a whim, he just copied
and pasted it into Google.

236
00:17:38,013 --> 00:17:41,147
One website came up,
and it was Chinese characters.

237
00:17:44,889 --> 00:17:46,369
So he clicked on it.

238
00:17:46,456 --> 00:17:47,414
[mouse clicks]

239
00:17:49,024 --> 00:17:52,854
To my surprise,
what came back
was the actual page

240
00:17:52,941 --> 00:17:57,163
that the attackers used
to interface
with the compromised systems.

241
