nonstop.

495
00:37:55,969 --> 00:37:58,493
That's why TwitCasting
was perfect.

496
00:38:00,321 --> 00:38:02,889
[chanting][speaks Portuguese]

497
00:38:02,976 --> 00:38:05,587
It's a very delicate moment here
in the Saens Peña square.

498
00:38:05,674 --> 00:38:10,026
People being prohibited
from walking to
or to leave the square.

499
00:38:10,113 --> 00:38:12,333
This image we are seeing here,

500
00:38:12,420 --> 00:38:15,597
a corridor of police
encircling the protest.

501
00:38:15,684 --> 00:38:20,036
[singing in Portuguese][indistinct]

502
00:38:20,123 --> 00:38:23,910
Looking at Brazil,
this is one of those cases
where you have

503
00:38:23,997 --> 00:38:26,129
a sporting event, in this case,

504
00:38:26,216 --> 00:38:31,265
which triggers all sorts of
extra concern around security

505
00:38:31,352 --> 00:38:34,486
and the control of information,
much of it legitimate.

506
00:38:34,573 --> 00:38:39,317
But what often happens is that
the layering of surveillance,

507
00:38:39,404 --> 00:38:42,581
extra-legal measures that
happens leading up to

508
00:38:42,668 --> 00:38:45,758
and during these events
doesn't just disappear.

509
00:38:45,845 --> 00:38:48,195
It becomes part of
the permanent architecture.

510
00:38:48,282 --> 00:38:51,416
[chanting in Portuguese]

511
00:38:57,683 --> 00:38:59,467
Can you tell me
what this is?

512
00:38:59,554 --> 00:39:02,427
No, I can't.Why not?

513
00:39:02,514 --> 00:39:09,695
It transmits live video
to the central command.

514
00:39:09,782 --> 00:39:11,914
That's all I know
about this equipment.

515
00:39:12,001 --> 00:39:16,397
[chanting in Portuguese]

516
00:39:16,484 --> 00:39:19,661
[Deibert]
Mobile phones are prevalent.
Everyone has one in their hands.

517
00:39:19,748 --> 00:39:22,925
And the police
now use a technique

518
00:39:23,012 --> 00:39:27,843
where they set up fake
cell phone towers that captures
everyone within the vicinity

519
00:39:27,930 --> 00:39:31,978
and gathers up
identifying information that's
emitted by the cell phones,

520
00:39:32,065 --> 00:39:34,110
which they then
use to track people

521
00:39:34,197 --> 00:39:36,461
and associate them
with each other

522
00:39:36,548 --> 00:39:39,899
and being at specific
physical events like a protest

523
00:39:39,986 --> 00:39:42,423
and the government
can go back in time

524
00:39:42,510 --> 00:39:47,341
and recreate
every facet of your life
on that particular day and hour.

525
00:39:47,428 --> 00:39:49,648
With whom
you were communicating.

526
00:39:49,735 --> 00:39:52,564
Not only
what you're broadcasting
but what you're saying privately

527
00:39:52,651 --> 00:39:55,349
and use this to incriminate you
down the road.

528
00:39:59,745 --> 00:40:04,271
[in Portuguese]
Nineteen people accused
of planning acts of vandalism

529
00:40:04,358 --> 00:40:06,839
were arrested today in Rio.

530
00:40:06,926 --> 00:40:08,754
[woman] It was just dawn

531
00:40:08,841 --> 00:40:14,542
when 30 police left to serve search and seizure warrants in Rio.

532
00:40:14,629 --> 00:40:18,328
They confiscated computers, cell phones,

533
00:40:18,416 --> 00:40:22,768
gas masks and one piece of wood with nails and other objects.

534
00:40:26,772 --> 00:40:32,038
Inside the police station here,
there's a new operational unit,

535
00:40:32,125 --> 00:40:37,304
which is
the Internet Crimes Unit.

536
00:40:37,391 --> 00:40:42,962
They attempt to transform
our youth, who want to see
a different country,

537
00:40:43,049 --> 00:40:46,792
into a gang
of marginalized criminals.

538
00:40:46,879 --> 00:40:51,057
Surveillance of the Internet,
mobile phones,

539
00:40:51,144 --> 00:40:53,538
manipulation of evidence.

540
00:40:58,978 --> 00:41:02,285
They are monitored,
phone-tapped and followed.

541
00:41:02,372 --> 00:41:04,331
Including the Ninjas.

542
00:41:04,418 --> 00:41:07,813
You can be sure their phones
are all tapped.

543
00:41:07,900 --> 00:41:10,729
That includes us as well.

544
00:41:10,816 --> 00:41:13,993
This surveillance,
this espionage,

545
00:41:14,080 --> 00:41:18,650
this paranoia
that's been imposed.

546
00:41:18,737 --> 00:41:21,348
People realize there's
some hidden mechanism of power

547
00:41:21,435 --> 00:41:23,959
going on through surveillance.

548
00:41:24,046 --> 00:41:27,746
And you begin to suspect, maybe,
this device you can't trust.

549
00:41:27,833 --> 00:41:30,923
Maybe the state's in here
or it's in my mobile phone or...

550
00:41:31,010 --> 00:41:33,534
And as that kind of
seeps out there,

551
00:41:33,621 --> 00:41:37,059
people become much more
unwilling to take risks.

552
00:41:37,146 --> 00:41:38,452
You know, even in our own work,

553
00:41:38,539 --> 00:41:41,629
we're much more cautious
about what we say over e-mail,

554
00:41:41,716 --> 00:41:43,936
worried that
somebody's listening and so on.

555
00:41:44,023 --> 00:41:47,635
It's like sand in the machinery.
It kind of slows things down

556
00:41:47,722 --> 00:41:50,725
and everything becomes
much more complicated,

557
00:41:50,812 --> 00:41:53,554
just to communicate
basic instructions.

558
00:41:53,641 --> 00:41:55,861
You're like, "Oh,
first I have to encrypt it."

559
00:41:57,689 --> 00:42:00,866
All these technologies too,
cryptography things,

560
00:42:00,953 --> 00:42:02,824
they might be getting cheap,

561
00:42:02,911 --> 00:42:08,003
but if we consider
in terms of time,
they are expensive.

562
00:42:08,090 --> 00:42:11,616
You know,
people are being murdered
every day in the favelas.

563
00:42:11,703 --> 00:42:14,662
The military police
are still running.

564
00:42:14,749 --> 00:42:18,057
So it's complicated now
to stop the machines

565
00:42:18,144 --> 00:42:21,321
and adapt our system
to a more safe mode.

566
00:42:25,717 --> 00:42:30,548
[crowd booing]

567
00:42:34,203 --> 00:42:37,555
[in Portuguese] These days
the media can police more
than the police themselves...

568
00:42:40,470 --> 00:42:43,169
by reproducing this idea
of the protester as enemy.

569
00:42:47,216 --> 00:42:50,350
The truth is tough to swallow!

570
00:42:50,437 --> 00:42:52,918
Globo supported
the dictatorship!

571
00:42:55,050 --> 00:43:00,926
[Bentes] History of O Globo,
started during
the military dictatorship,

572
00:43:01,013 --> 00:43:05,104
it was the media arm
of the dictatorship,

573
00:43:05,191 --> 00:43:09,848
and they think
they're as powerful
as the government.

574
00:43:09,935 --> 00:43:13,852
We say if you hate the media,
then become the media.

575
00:43:17,290 --> 00:43:21,686
♪ Oh, my, oh  I'll go for what you know♪

576
00:43:21,773 --> 00:43:26,908
♪ Who I owe  Why own when you can just♪

577
00:43:26,995 --> 00:43:27,866
♪ Sell it♪

578
00:43:36,396 --> 00:43:38,485
[in Portuguese]
We've just had many bombs
explode.

579
00:43:38,572 --> 00:43:42,097
There were many aggressions
we just witnessed,

580
00:43:42,184 --> 00:43:45,405
many rubber bullets shot
one on top of the other.

581
00:43:45,492 --> 00:43:48,887
As soon as the bomb exploded,
the arbitrariness commenced,

582
00:43:48,974 --> 00:43:51,193
the physical aggressions
during searches.

583
00:43:51,280 --> 00:43:54,936
No one is being aggressive.
No, you are talking smack!

584
00:43:55,023 --> 00:43:58,461
-No one was
physically aggressive here!
-Let me report what I've seen.

585
00:43:58,548 --> 00:44:00,594
You've already unleashed
such a shitload of violence.

586
00:44:00,681 --> 00:44:03,989
And you're not going to
revoke my right
to free expression,

587
00:44:04,076 --> 00:44:08,123
my right to do my job
as the free media,
the media activist that I am.

588
00:44:08,210 --> 00:44:09,908
My name is Felipe Pecanha
if you want to know.

589
00:44:14,434 --> 00:44:17,524
[man]
♪ Those gloves  Just take 'em off♪

590
00:44:17,611 --> 00:44:19,569
♪ Move before  The city moves to us♪

591
00:44:19,657 --> 00:44:24,357
There behind me, yet another
situation of pandemonium,
people screaming.

592
00:44:25,793 --> 00:44:27,447
♪ To us, to us♪

593
00:44:30,406 --> 00:44:33,018
[explosion]

594
00:44:33,105 --> 00:44:38,023
-[horns playing]
-[helicopter flying over]

595
00:44:38,110 --> 00:44:42,114
[shouting]

596
00:44:44,072 --> 00:44:48,381
[shouting in Portuguese,
indistinct]

597
00:44:52,907 --> 00:44:54,692
What are they doing downstairs?

598
00:44:54,779 --> 00:44:56,694
I got beat up down there!

599
00:44:56,781 --> 00:44:58,260
[woman] Open! Open!

600
00:45:01,829 --> 00:45:04,919
What's happening
in there?They are beating up everyone.

601
00:45:10,664 --> 00:45:12,622
Don't touch me!

602
00:45:13,928 --> 00:45:17,149
Sit down!

603
00:45:18,498 --> 00:45:19,934
Did they beat you?

604
00:45:20,021 --> 00:45:23,851
Yes, a lot!
I was trying to protect myself.

605
00:45:31,467 --> 00:45:37,996
The police have no shame.
No shame, committing
these savage acts.

606
00:45:46,352 --> 00:45:51,183
Whoa, don't take me.
Whoa, brother.
What's going on?

607
00:45:53,272 --> 00:45:55,187
They're arresting me!

608
00:45:56,014 --> 00:45:58,407
They're kicking me!

609
00:46:00,670 --> 00:46:01,759
They're kicking me!

610
00:46:01,846 --> 00:46:07,199
They're crushing my phone!
What is this?

611
00:46:14,075 --> 00:46:16,512
I was just attacked by
eight of you, ten of you,

612
00:46:16,599 --> 00:46:19,820
big, armed men in uniform.

613
00:46:19,907 --> 00:46:23,215
I didn't do anything wrong
to any of you!

614
00:46:23,302 --> 00:46:26,305
I am transmitting live
on the Internet
with a cell phone.

615
00:46:26,392 --> 00:46:29,787
This is not
any kind of violence.
This is not a crime.

616
00:46:29,874 --> 00:46:33,660
This is a constitutional right
of the citizen.

617
00:46:33,747 --> 00:46:36,750
The military police here in Rio
are a disgrace.

618
00:46:38,534 --> 00:46:41,189
[crowd applauding]

619
00:46:41,276 --> 00:46:44,062
[Deibert]
So at the same time
that you have so many people

620
00:46:44,149 --> 00:46:48,631
able to communicate to
a global audience at an instant,

621
00:46:48,718 --> 00:46:53,288
governments, in ways that
they weren't 20 years ago,

622
00:46:53,375 --> 00:46:58,511
are really ramping up
information controls
because they see...

623
00:46:58,598 --> 00:47:01,383
And when we say "governments,"
we're really talking about
entrenched powers,

624
00:47:01,470 --> 00:47:06,345
institutionalized, uh, you know,
forms of capitalism in the state

625
00:47:06,432 --> 00:47:09,348
that see, you know,

626
00:47:09,435 --> 00:47:13,787
this type of
unpredictable citizen activism
as a threat to their interests

627
00:47:13,874 --> 00:47:16,094
and are developing ways
to counter it.

628
00:47:18,618 --> 00:47:20,663
[announcer] You have new challenges today.

629
00:47:22,491 --> 00:47:26,104
Sensitive data is transmitted over encrypted channels.

630
00:47:27,192 --> 00:47:29,890
You need more.

631
00:47:29,977 --> 00:47:32,675
You want to look through your target's eyes.

632
00:47:35,026 --> 00:47:36,941
You have to hack your target.

633
00:47:42,990 --> 00:47:47,212
You have to overcome encryption and capture relevant data.

634
00:47:48,996 --> 00:47:51,781
Being stealth and untraceable.

635
00:47:55,133 --> 00:47:57,091
Exactly what we do.

636
00:48:02,662 --> 00:48:07,319
The vendors of
these products and services
market them to governments,

637
00:48:07,406 --> 00:48:09,277
usually at trade shows

638
00:48:09,364 --> 00:48:13,325
that are only open
to accredited law enforcement
and intelligence agencies.

639
00:48:13,412 --> 00:48:17,068
Actually, I've got
a big binder that I can...

640
00:48:17,155 --> 00:48:19,766
So, if you ignore the bag,
actually which...

641
00:48:19,853 --> 00:48:21,246
[chuckling]

642
00:48:21,333 --> 00:48:25,467
...someone, uh, deposited
these in as a gift to me,

643
00:48:25,554 --> 00:48:29,428
but I think
was hoping to disguise it
in the kindergarten bag.

644
00:48:29,515 --> 00:48:35,303
These are brochures
from the type of trade shows
that we're talking about,

645
00:48:35,390 --> 00:48:39,481
products and services that allow
cell phone detection,

646
00:48:39,568 --> 00:48:41,875
uh, insertion of malware...

647
00:48:44,138 --> 00:48:47,185
tracking,
social media monitoring.

648
00:48:47,272 --> 00:48:50,188
In many ways, the way to
think about this market

649
00:48:50,275 --> 00:48:53,800
is that it's
the commercialization
of cyber crime.

650
00:48:53,887 --> 00:48:57,673
You trick somebody into
installing a software program

651
00:48:57,760 --> 00:48:59,806
that contains malicious code

652
00:48:59,893 --> 00:49:02,374
that exploits some vulnerability
in the system,

653
00:49:02,461 --> 00:49:06,378
which then allows the attacker
to do anything they want.

654
00:49:06,465 --> 00:49:09,859
Turn on the webcam,
listen in on the microphone,

655
00:49:09,947 --> 00:49:14,081
record keystrokes,
record the location,
the movement.

656
00:49:14,168 --> 00:49:16,605
It operates without
much accountability,

657
00:49:16,692 --> 00:49:20,174
certainly no corporate
social responsibility,

658
00:49:20,261 --> 00:49:23,264
ripe for abuse in a place
like Sudan or Ethiopia.

659
00:49:23,351 --> 00:49:25,788
We've seen in one
case after another,

660
00:49:25,875 --> 00:49:28,878
how this ends up being used
to target civil society.

661
00:49:28,966 --> 00:49:29,967
Aha.

662
00:49:31,533 --> 00:49:33,100
Gamma Group.

663
00:49:33,187 --> 00:49:36,060
Maker of the notorious
FinFisher spyware.

664
00:49:36,147 --> 00:49:37,931
[cars honking]

665
00:49:56,732 --> 00:49:59,822
The whole history...

666
00:49:59,909 --> 00:50:02,216
my personal history,
my family history

667
00:50:02,303 --> 00:50:05,654
and my organization's history
is written with surveillance.

668
00:50:18,580 --> 00:50:20,974
In Ethiopia,
there is only one server.

669
00:50:21,061 --> 00:50:23,629
Every telecommunication
connection

670
00:50:23,716 --> 00:50:27,111
passes through
the Ethiopian
telecommunications server.

671
00:50:27,198 --> 00:50:32,246
And that server is
highly controlled.

672
00:50:32,333 --> 00:50:35,380
When you talk to a friend,
you know that somebody
is hearing.

673
00:50:35,467 --> 00:50:37,817
When you write an e-mail,

674
00:50:37,904 --> 00:50:40,254
you suspect that somebody
might have read it

675
00:50:40,341 --> 00:50:43,170
and that somebody
wants to hunt you down.

676
00:51:02,015 --> 00:51:05,497
And when I came to the UK,

677
00:51:05,584 --> 00:51:09,153
there was a total liberation
of that stress.

678
00:51:09,240 --> 00:51:12,591
I felt,
"I am living in a free country

679
00:51:12,678 --> 00:51:15,028
where the privacy of individuals
is respected

680
00:51:16,203 --> 00:51:18,423
and my privacy is
also respected."

681
00:51:19,206 --> 00:51:20,642
But I was wrong.

682
00:51:24,255 --> 00:51:27,040
Sometime in 2013,

683
00:51:27,127 --> 00:51:32,437
we started to find
some of the things that we
discussed among a small circle

684
00:51:32,524 --> 00:51:37,181
in open media
and in unfriendly medias
of the Ethiopian government.

685
00:51:40,488 --> 00:51:43,230
You don't want to
suspect your friend,
but you have to.

686
00:51:45,319 --> 00:51:48,757
And we keep on wondering
how they could find out.

687
00:51:51,586 --> 00:51:55,634
We got the answer
from a totally unexpected area.

688
00:51:55,721 --> 00:51:59,899
A certain group of people
goes to Citizen Lab.

689
00:51:59,986 --> 00:52:03,555
And they published a report.

690
00:52:03,642 --> 00:52:07,472
And in that report
there was my photograph,

691
00:52:07,559 --> 00:52:12,651
and they used it
to attach with the spyware

692
00:52:12,738 --> 00:52:15,132
and distribute it
among the Ethiopian community.

693
00:52:19,005 --> 00:52:23,836
The attacker has to socially
engineer or convince the target

694
00:52:23,923 --> 00:52:28,580
to open a file or to,
you know, click through
some security warning,

695
00:52:28,667 --> 00:52:31,148
um, in order to become infected.

696
00:52:31,235 --> 00:52:36,370
We had found a document
that had pictures of Ethiopian
opposition leaders in it,

697
00:52:36,457 --> 00:52:38,851
and it looked like
it was targeted
and designed to appeal

698
00:52:38,938 --> 00:52:41,245
to members of
the Ethiopian diaspora.

699
00:52:41,332 --> 00:52:44,030
Uh, but in fact,
the file was cleverly disguised

700
00:52:44,117 --> 00:52:46,728
to look like a document
that's actually
a computer program,

701
00:52:46,815 --> 00:52:48,426
an executable file.

702
00:52:48,513 --> 00:52:50,732
So when you run this,
it will install software
on your computer

703
00:52:50,819 --> 00:52:53,387
even though, you know, they
changed the icon and everything

704
00:52:53,474 --> 00:52:56,521
to make it look like
this is a document
or a picture.

705
00:52:56,608 --> 00:52:57,783
This is actually a program.

706
00:53:01,700 --> 00:53:03,963
After that,
I just tried to scan...

707
00:53:05,617 --> 00:53:09,098
people who were arrested
after my departure.

708
00:53:10,839 --> 00:53:14,887
I had a friend in Saudi Arabia
who was sent back to Ethiopia,

709
00:53:14,974 --> 00:53:17,629
and arrested and
sentenced to 18 years.

710
00:53:17,716 --> 00:53:20,632
And I started to question,
probably it was because of me.

711
00:53:23,722 --> 00:53:25,027
And he's not the only person.

712
00:53:32,121 --> 00:53:35,255
I was able to look at the memory
of an infected computer.

713
00:53:35,342 --> 00:53:38,171
In other words,
what's going on inside
the computer when it's infected.

714
00:53:38,258 --> 00:53:42,480
And I was able to identify
several interesting artifacts
in the memory,

715
00:53:42,567 --> 00:53:45,700
including a bunch of strings
that said "FinFisher," "FinSpy,"

716
00:53:45,787 --> 00:53:48,137
very clearly attributing this
to the company.

717
00:53:51,402 --> 00:53:55,057
Ethiopia is
one of the poorest countries
in the world.

718
00:53:55,144 --> 00:54:00,498
Internet users in Ethiopia
are less than two percent.

719
00:54:00,585 --> 00:54:03,152
It is the lowest in the world.

720
00:54:03,240 --> 00:54:09,115
But they spend
millions of dollars
for FinFisher.

721
00:54:09,202 --> 00:54:14,729
For spying on people like me,
who are trying to do...

722
00:54:14,816 --> 00:54:19,168
to bring a better future
to Ethiopia.

723
00:54:24,130 --> 00:54:27,960
You don't have to be the NSA to
get inside somebody's computer.

724
00:54:28,047 --> 00:54:31,355
Um, instead you can
exploit their curiosity,

725
00:54:31,442 --> 00:54:35,228
their, um, need to communicate.

726
00:54:35,315 --> 00:54:38,753
And of course,
journalists, at the very heart
of what they do,

727
00:54:38,840 --> 00:54:42,757
is engage in communication
with a lot of people

728
00:54:42,844 --> 00:54:45,630
and a lot of people that
they don't know and trust
necessarily.

729
00:54:45,717 --> 00:54:49,024
Because they're engaged
in outreach and communicating
constantly with sources.

730
00:54:49,111 --> 00:54:51,288
[crowd shouting]

731
00:54:57,729 --> 00:55:00,079
[cheering, whistling]

732
00:55:02,647 --> 00:55:06,477
Fifty years ago,
nobody would have known
what happened in Syria.

733
00:55:06,564 --> 00:55:10,611
But in 2011, when it started,
everybody had Facebook.

734
00:55:10,698 --> 00:55:16,313
Everybody has e-mails
and everybody has WhatsApp
and Viber.

735
00:55:17,618 --> 00:55:19,490
So you just can't stop people

736
00:55:19,577 --> 00:55:22,362
from telling
what is happening to them.

737
00:55:22,449 --> 00:55:25,365
So when they besieged Daraa
at the beginning,

738
00:55:25,452 --> 00:55:30,065
they shut down communication,
Internet, land lines
and even electricity.

739
00:55:30,152 --> 00:55:34,331
But they did not know that
in the 21st century,
people have their ways.

740
00:55:34,418 --> 00:55:37,464
People were charging
their mobiles from their cars
or generators,

741
00:55:37,551 --> 00:55:40,989
hand generators,
um, manual generators.

742
00:55:41,076 --> 00:55:44,993
And people were using
satellite connections.

743
00:55:45,080 --> 00:55:49,694
You don't need to use
the country, uh, Internet
to be connected to the Internet.

744
00:55:49,781 --> 00:55:51,217
You can use anything.

745
00:55:51,304 --> 00:55:55,221
And they were able to tell
what was happening to them.

746
00:55:55,308 --> 00:56:00,922
Um, so the story got around.

747
00:56:01,009 --> 00:56:02,968
[man speaking foreign language]

748
00:56:03,055 --> 00:56:05,144
[sirens blaring]

749
00:56:09,453 --> 00:56:13,239
A few years ago many of us
celebrated the Arab Spring

750
00:56:13,326 --> 00:56:16,416
as the paradigm of what
these technologies could do.

751
00:56:16,503 --> 00:56:19,637
Remember
we called it at the time
"liberation technology."

752
00:56:19,724 --> 00:56:21,813
It would bring about the end
of authoritarian rule.

753
00:56:21,900 --> 00:56:23,728
[man speaking Arabic]

754
00:56:29,777 --> 00:56:35,522
Unfortunately,
Syria has become the
Arab Spring's dark aftermath.

755
00:56:35,609 --> 00:56:36,784
[explosion]

756
00:56:36,871 --> 00:56:40,658
[boy shouting in Arabic]

757
00:56:42,660 --> 00:56:45,924
As groups
sympathetic to the Assad regime

758
00:56:46,011 --> 00:56:50,276
have employed
off-the-shelf malware crime kits
to infiltrate social networks,

759
00:56:50,363 --> 00:56:53,671
arrest, torture and
murder opposition groups

760
00:56:53,758 --> 00:56:55,673
and even target
their air strikes.

761
00:57:03,463 --> 00:57:04,377
[rifles cocking]

762
00:57:10,165 --> 00:57:11,036
[shouting]

763
00:57:19,871 --> 00:57:21,220
[gunshot]

764
00:57:24,919 --> 00:57:28,619
[man] From the beginning,
we believed that the camera
is the most powerful weapon,

765
00:57:28,706 --> 00:57:31,012
and it was actually
the only weapon we have

766
00:57:31,099 --> 00:57:33,014
to deliver our own message
to the whole world.

767
00:57:41,109 --> 00:57:42,763
This is interesting.

768
00:57:42,850 --> 00:57:44,548
Baraa?

769
00:57:44,635 --> 00:57:45,766
[speaking Arabic]

770
00:57:49,248 --> 00:57:54,079
It's a pleasure for me
to introduce
one of my best friends,

771
00:57:54,166 --> 00:57:59,563
Mr. Baraa,
he's one of the most activist
people inside Syria.

772
00:57:59,650 --> 00:58:02,783
He came a few days ago
'cause he has...

773
00:58:02,870 --> 00:58:08,180
He has... many broken
bones on his body.

774
00:58:08,267 --> 00:58:10,704
[gunfire]

775
00:58:10,791 --> 00:58:13,838
He was there and covered
the battle in Daraa City.

776
00:58:17,406 --> 00:58:20,279
And in the afternoon,
they get a tank shell.

777
00:58:20,366 --> 00:58:21,585
[explosion]

778
00:58:23,238 --> 00:58:26,807
He was with his friend,
whom has this camera.

779
00:58:28,374 --> 00:58:30,463
And that good guy, you know,
he gets killed

780
00:58:30,550 --> 00:58:33,858
by one tank shell
from the regime's side.

781
00:58:33,945 --> 00:58:35,163
[gunfire]

782
00:58:36,861 --> 00:58:38,558
This video, you will see now,

783
00:58:38,645 --> 00:58:42,954
a remote control car and
it exploded, a huge explosion.

784
00:58:44,651 --> 00:58:46,218
It was filmed
by this camera.

785
00:58:48,307 --> 00:58:49,308
[explosion]

786
00:58:50,962 --> 00:58:51,963
After that,

787
00:58:52,050 --> 00:58:54,226
the rocket launchers

788
00:58:54,313 --> 00:58:56,228
started to hit the place
from the regime's side.

789
00:58:57,534 --> 00:59:01,233
So our activist, this media guy,

790
00:59:01,320 --> 00:59:04,584
he gets killed in here
in this exact... this place.

791
00:59:04,671 --> 00:59:07,413
Now here.
He was standing here.

792
00:59:07,500 --> 00:59:10,242
And people found
the camera with him.

793
00:59:10,329 --> 00:59:12,766
We took out the memory card,
and we post this...

794
00:59:14,072 --> 00:59:16,553
as, you know,
in memory of Hussain.

795
00:59:20,295 --> 00:59:22,776
[wreckage clattering]

796
00:59:31,916 --> 00:59:35,963
So now, Mr. Baraa here,
just a few days just to heal.

797
00:59:36,050 --> 00:59:40,446
He paid a visit
to some hospitals
to check out himself,

798
00:59:40,533 --> 00:59:44,276
then he will go back into Syria
to keep working.

799
00:59:46,147 --> 00:59:48,802
There is a war on Facebook.

800
00:59:48,889 --> 00:59:54,242
Uh, every side is using Facebook
to promote themselves.

801
00:59:54,329 --> 00:59:58,246
They say on Facebook
that the army now controls
a certain area.

802
00:59:58,333 --> 01:00:01,902
So the rebels all go to that
certain area. Even though
it's still rebel-controlled.

803
01:00:01,989 --> 01:00:04,339
They start bombing it, even
though it's under their control.

804
01:00:04,426 --> 01:00:05,819
Then they withdraw from it.

805
01:00:05,906 --> 01:00:09,127
The other way around,
the regime will say,

806
01:00:09,214 --> 01:00:13,087
"We will occupy this area.
We will take over this area."

807
01:00:13,174 --> 01:00:16,177
Then the FSA would leave because
they're afraid of bombardment.

808
01:00:16,264 --> 01:00:17,265
It's just a game.

809
01:00:18,353 --> 01:00:19,616
Facebook is a game.

810
01:00:29,016 --> 01:00:30,409
[Wjd]
It was just a silly joke I made.

811
01:00:31,889 --> 01:00:35,501
I didn't hurt anybody.
I didn't insult anyone.

812
01:00:35,588 --> 01:00:39,548
It was not political.
It was not racist.

813
01:00:39,636 --> 01:00:42,464
There is nothing
that they could hold against me

814
01:00:42,551 --> 01:00:44,423
with a thing that
I wrote on Facebook.

815
01:00:46,468 --> 01:00:50,124
But still,
at a time of war...

816
01:00:52,344 --> 01:00:53,432
people get crazy.

817
01:01:02,006 --> 01:01:06,358
They did not drag me
in the street or kidnap me.

818
01:01:06,445 --> 01:01:09,578
They just asked me to come
to ask me a few questions.

819
01:01:09,666 --> 01:01:12,451
This is what they said,
so I signed the paper
that I'm coming.

820
01:01:12,538 --> 01:01:18,631
I went
the next morning at 11:30,
to the detention center.

821
01:01:20,241 --> 01:01:22,243
The security guy came to me.

822
01:01:22,330 --> 01:01:25,769
He's like...
He's like half of my height.

823
01:01:25,856 --> 01:01:28,075
He blindfolded me,
and I was like,

824
01:01:28,162 --> 01:01:31,513
I was okay with that
because I thought, it's some...

825
01:01:31,600 --> 01:01:37,302
it's confidential secrets
of the country
that they don't want me to see.

826
01:01:37,389 --> 01:01:41,959
And then I was presented
to the detective
or the interrogator.

827
01:01:42,829 --> 01:01:43,787
I never saw him.

828
01:01:46,877 --> 01:01:51,229
He told me,
"You're a computer engineer.
Please be seated."

829
01:01:51,316 --> 01:01:55,929
And I sat next to him
and he started reading
all my Facebook posts.

830
01:01:56,016 --> 01:01:57,017
I was like, "Oh."

831
01:02:08,899 --> 01:02:11,075
One of the posts
that I wrote was,

832
01:02:11,162 --> 01:02:14,165
"No praying, no fasting
until the regime falls,"

833
01:02:14,252 --> 01:02:15,949
which was actually
making fun of both sides.

834
01:02:16,907 --> 01:02:18,299
And I laughed and he's like,

835
01:02:18,386 --> 01:02:21,085
"I'm not kidding with you.
I'm not joking with you."

836
01:02:24,523 --> 01:02:26,786
He kicked me on my chest

837
01:02:26,873 --> 01:02:31,922
and then he requested
the same short guy,

838
01:02:32,009 --> 01:02:33,880
because he was
there in the room,

839
01:02:33,967 --> 01:02:35,839
to bring something called
the "flying carpet,"

840
01:02:35,926 --> 01:02:37,579
which is a torturing machine.

841
01:02:37,666 --> 01:02:42,280
It's a wooden board,
like the door,

842
01:02:42,367 --> 01:02:45,413
but it has joints in the middle
that can flip.

843
01:02:46,327 --> 01:02:50,462
And I had to lay on it.

844
01:02:50,549 --> 01:02:54,858
They tied my wrists and
they tied me from the middle,
they tied my legs.

845
01:02:54,945 --> 01:02:59,601
And they just closed it
so my knees touched my chest.

846
01:02:59,688 --> 01:03:01,995
He took off my shoes
and my socks

847
01:03:02,082 --> 01:03:07,566
and started beating me
with a metal,
uh, with a metal whip.

848
01:03:10,134 --> 01:03:14,051
The pain is unbelievable.

849
01:03:15,139 --> 01:03:16,662
You just can't take it anymore.

850
01:03:16,749 --> 01:03:20,709
You just can't endure
this amount of agony.

851
01:03:29,240 --> 01:03:32,591
What we saw in Syria
was a lot of use of, say,

852
01:03:32,678 --> 01:03:34,898
off-the-shelf remote access
tools.

853
01:03:34,985 --> 01:03:38,466
So this is sort of software
that you can get from
underground message boards

854
01:03:38,553 --> 01:03:40,947
or maybe purchased
for not so much money.

855
01:03:41,034 --> 01:03:44,995
Maybe $200-300 that
give you the ability

856
01:03:45,082 --> 01:03:47,911
to record someone's keystrokes,
read their e-mails,

857
01:03:47,998 --> 01:03:51,131
even look at them
through their webcam.

858
01:03:51,218 --> 01:03:53,699
Record via
the computer's microphone,

859
01:03:53,786 --> 01:03:56,528
conversations that are being had
around the target's computer.

860
01:03:57,834 --> 01:04:00,227
Frequently what you would see

861
01:04:00,314 --> 01:04:03,013
is it would be bundled
with some type of lured document

862
01:04:03,100 --> 01:04:07,321
which showed
a deep understanding

863
01:04:07,408 --> 01:04:10,150
of the psychology of the people
they were trying to target.

864
01:04:10,237 --> 01:04:15,025
For instance, one of
the documents that was sent out
that I keenly recall

865
01:04:15,112 --> 01:04:17,462
was a list.

866
01:04:17,549 --> 01:04:23,468
A purported list
of insurgents identified
by the Syrian government.

867
01:04:23,555 --> 01:04:28,429
So of course what happened was
that this was promptly passed
around

868
01:04:28,516 --> 01:04:31,606
to all sorts of very
interesting groups in Syria

869
01:04:31,693 --> 01:04:34,609
because everyone wanted to know
if they were on this list
or not.

870
01:04:34,696 --> 01:04:40,311
So the actual spyware
payload itself wasn't
particularly sophisticated

871
01:04:40,398 --> 01:04:43,444
but the social...

872
01:04:43,531 --> 01:04:46,752
the social
and social engineering side
of that operation,

873
01:04:46,839 --> 01:04:48,885
um, was quite smart.

874
01:04:55,326 --> 01:04:58,851
Internet entered almost
all countries in the region

875
01:04:59,896 --> 01:05:01,245
before it entered Syria.

876
01:05:02,507 --> 01:05:03,464
Yes.

877
01:05:03,551 --> 01:05:05,902
Government in Syria,

878
01:05:05,989 --> 01:05:08,252
we are not as developed
as Canada, for example,

879
01:05:08,339 --> 01:05:10,341
or not as developed
as United States.

880
01:05:10,428 --> 01:05:13,431
In Canada
they can monitor people
and control people

881
01:05:13,518 --> 01:05:16,260
and spy people in
a very intelligent way.

882
01:05:16,347 --> 01:05:18,871
And even they don't
feel that they are...

883
01:05:21,700 --> 01:05:23,093
spied on.

884
01:05:23,180 --> 01:05:27,924
But in Syria,
of course you go to old ways.

885
01:05:34,669 --> 01:05:37,455
They untie me and then I was...

886
01:05:37,542 --> 01:05:40,153
and then he asked me to
sit next to him, and he said,

887
01:05:40,240 --> 01:05:41,198
"Let's start talking."

888
01:05:43,156 --> 01:05:46,551
And I told him,
"I don't want to
talk to you anymore."

889
01:05:46,638 --> 01:05:52,949
He said, "I want you
to admit you work with the Free
Syrian Electronic Army."

890
01:05:53,036 --> 01:05:55,516
I was like,
"I don't know what that is."

891
01:05:55,603 --> 01:05:58,911
He said, "You like their page.
You like their page
on Facebook."

892
01:06:00,260 --> 01:06:02,219
I told him,
"I like their page on Facebook,

893
01:06:02,306 --> 01:06:05,309
but there are too many pages
on Facebook that you can like.

894
01:06:05,396 --> 01:06:07,920
I also like Assad's page
on Facebook."

895
01:06:09,530 --> 01:06:12,011
Well, that did not convince him.

896
01:06:12,098 --> 01:06:17,190
So his boss came
and he told him,
"What is going on?"

897
01:06:17,277 --> 01:06:21,586
He told him,
"This is the Facebook guy,
and he's not cooperating."

898
01:06:21,673 --> 01:06:25,938
So then his boss told him to,
"Send him down to the basement,

899
01:06:26,025 --> 01:06:29,942
peel his skin off and just
remind me of him after a month."

900
01:06:30,029 --> 01:06:32,466
And I was like, "Can we go
back to the flying carpet?"

901
01:06:32,553 --> 01:06:33,424
[chuckles]

902
01:06:36,035 --> 01:06:37,819
I stayed there
for almost a month,

903
01:06:37,906 --> 01:06:41,301
and then I was released
with a presidential amnesty.

904
01:06:43,477 --> 01:06:46,263
So I went in a taxi,

905
01:06:46,350 --> 01:06:50,441
covered with dust,
dirt, shit and blood,

906
01:06:50,528 --> 01:06:53,966
all over my face,
my clothes.

907
01:06:54,053 --> 01:06:58,144
And then the taxi driver
felt pity for me,
and he gave me a cigarette.

908
01:06:58,231 --> 01:07:00,233
I remember
that was the first time I cried.

909
01:07:03,497 --> 01:07:07,501
And I went to my flat in Latakia
where I used to study,

910
01:07:07,588 --> 01:07:09,373
and my roommates
were shocked
to see me alive.

911
01:07:11,244 --> 01:07:15,118
And then, like,
two weeks after that
I fled the country.

912
01:07:16,467 --> 01:07:17,990
I came to Jordan.

913
01:07:18,077 --> 01:07:19,122
I am a journalist now.

914
01:07:32,570 --> 01:07:36,139
[man] With Syria,
a lot of the bad things
that are happening

915
01:07:36,226 --> 01:07:39,359
are happening to people
who don't look
like Westerners.

916
01:07:39,446 --> 01:07:43,059
The bad things happening to
these people through technology,

917
01:07:43,146 --> 01:07:46,410
through the risks
inherent in technology,

918
01:07:46,497 --> 01:07:49,500
are not different
than the kinds of risks
that we may face,

919
01:07:49,587 --> 01:07:51,806
um, although they look
different.

920
01:07:51,893 --> 01:07:53,199
We see in the news
almost every day,

921
01:07:53,286 --> 01:07:56,855
a report of a breach,
some kind of a large hack.

922
01:07:56,942 --> 01:07:59,292
Data being exploited somewhere.

923
01:07:59,379 --> 01:08:02,121
It's the same problem,
but in Syria,
it looks very different

924
01:08:02,208 --> 01:08:04,776
and because there are
dark skinned people,

925
01:08:04,863 --> 01:08:07,431
uh, and there are guns
and a foreign language,

926
01:08:07,518 --> 01:08:10,434
it feels, I think to many,
exotic and different,

927
01:08:10,521 --> 01:08:12,044
and it couldn't happen here.

928
01:08:12,131 --> 01:08:14,568
And I think, in fact,
what you're seeing in Syria

929
01:08:14,655 --> 01:08:17,571
is this is what happens
when the risks get higher

930
01:08:17,658 --> 01:08:19,182
but the technology is the same.

931
01:08:20,618 --> 01:08:22,010
They're using the same Facebook
that we are.

932
01:08:24,056 --> 01:08:25,362
[chattering]

933
01:08:32,064 --> 01:08:34,284
[in Portuguese]
My name is Bruno,
for those who don't know me.

934
01:08:34,371 --> 01:08:38,679
[man beat boxing]

935
01:08:38,766 --> 01:08:43,989
I'd been attending protests
for a month,
a month full of protests.

936
01:08:44,076 --> 01:08:48,733
It's good to have protection,
in case police repression
is very strong.

937
01:08:50,604 --> 01:08:53,129
When the professor asked
the class what they thought,

938
01:08:53,216 --> 01:08:55,827
people were
against the protestors.

939
01:08:55,914 --> 01:08:59,700
I improvised a chest protector
with aluminum.

940
01:09:02,486 --> 01:09:05,619
I said, "Whoa, you didn't
even go to the protests.

941
01:09:05,706 --> 01:09:07,273
It's not like you describe it."

942
01:09:08,361 --> 01:09:10,842
So I decided to make a video,

943
01:09:10,929 --> 01:09:15,151
to document a protest
for those who didn't attend.

944
01:09:20,895 --> 01:09:23,985
[chattering]

945
01:09:27,641 --> 01:09:29,600
I'm arriving now
at Largo do Machado.

946
01:09:29,687 --> 01:09:31,384
[woman shouting in Portuguese]

947
01:09:31,471 --> 01:09:32,820
Lot's of different people here.

948
01:09:36,389 --> 01:09:38,304
[singing in foreign language]

949
01:09:41,394 --> 01:09:43,744
[shouting on microphone]

950
01:09:47,748 --> 01:09:49,881
[man shouting in Portuguese]

951
01:09:54,494 --> 01:09:57,628
They have shut down
all the lights
to intimidate the crowd,

952
01:09:57,715 --> 01:09:59,020
but we're not going to leave.

953
01:10:00,370 --> 01:10:02,676
Only when the people become one!

954
01:10:03,547 --> 01:10:05,679
And not two peoples...

955
01:10:05,766 --> 01:10:10,467
where the rich
use the poor against the poor.

956
01:10:11,903 --> 01:10:15,689
Because we are strong!
We are not weak!

957
01:10:15,776 --> 01:10:17,300
[upbeat intro]

958
01:10:18,301 --> 01:10:19,650
♪ Satisfied♪

959
01:10:19,737 --> 01:10:21,478
♪ Satisfied♪

960
01:10:21,565 --> 01:10:23,175
♪ Satisfied♪

961
01:10:26,787 --> 01:10:28,006
[gunshot]

962
01:10:29,268 --> 01:10:30,878
[man singing]

963
01:10:30,965 --> 01:10:32,489
[glass shattering]

964
01:10:35,883 --> 01:10:37,842
[all shouting]

965
01:10:41,367 --> 01:10:42,890
[screaming]

966
01:10:45,850 --> 01:10:47,852
[sirens chirping]

967
01:10:55,033 --> 01:10:59,690
[Teles] I hadn't done anything,
but police pursued me.

968
01:11:01,518 --> 01:11:03,259
I'm a pacifist.
I don't like violence.

969
01:11:04,782 --> 01:11:08,786
But I'll defend myself
if I have to. So I ran.

970
01:11:08,873 --> 01:11:11,571
[woman speaking Portuguese]
What is this? This is surreal.

971
01:11:11,658 --> 01:11:13,530
[singing continues]

972
01:11:14,444 --> 01:11:17,534
[clapping rhythmically]

973
01:11:17,621 --> 01:11:20,537
[singing continues, indistinct]

974
01:11:24,367 --> 01:11:29,763
♪ Satisfied♪

975
01:11:30,634 --> 01:11:31,983
[shouting]

976
01:11:33,898 --> 01:11:35,073
[shouting in Portuguese]

977
01:11:39,773 --> 01:11:41,949
-[shouting]
-[shutters clicking]

978
01:11:53,831 --> 01:11:55,354
[news intro]

979
01:11:55,441 --> 01:11:56,921
[in Portuguese]
The protest took place

980
01:11:57,008 --> 01:11:58,314
outside
the governor's palace.

981
01:11:58,401 --> 01:12:01,708
It started peacefully
but ended in confrontation.

982
01:12:01,795 --> 01:12:04,276
[man] A battle began. On one side, rocks being thrown,

983
01:12:04,363 --> 01:12:06,409
on the other side, rubber bullets.

984
01:12:06,496 --> 01:12:10,413
The masked bandits threw Molotov cocktails at the police.

985
01:12:11,675 --> 01:12:13,764
One policeman was hit by the fire.

986
01:12:13,851 --> 01:12:19,117
The military police found a bag with Molotov cocktails.

987
01:12:19,204 --> 01:12:20,945
-[police officer]
You should film this.
-[reporter] What is it?

988
01:12:21,032 --> 01:12:23,600
Molotov cocktails.
These kill cops.

989
01:12:23,687 --> 01:12:25,689
[shouting]

990
01:12:27,952 --> 01:12:32,565
He threw the first
Molotov cocktail! He threw
the first Molotov cocktail!

991
01:12:32,652 --> 01:12:34,175
I wasn't even there!

992
01:12:34,262 --> 01:12:37,962
I wasn't carrying a backpack.
Someone attacked me.

993
01:12:38,049 --> 01:12:41,661
Don't say anything else,
my friend.

994
01:12:41,748 --> 01:12:43,315
[sirens wailing]

995
01:12:50,278 --> 01:12:51,976
[shouting]

996
01:12:52,063 --> 01:12:54,674
[in English]
Lots of people were there,
by 7:00 in the night,

997
01:12:55,675 --> 01:12:58,374
and we were live.

998
01:12:58,461 --> 01:13:02,900
[Carioca] We are here
transmitting live to 5,000
viewers with a mobile phone.

999
01:13:02,987 --> 01:13:07,252
[Silva]
Suddenly a man came to Carioca,
and he asked to interview him.

1000
01:13:07,339 --> 01:13:10,995
[Carioca]
Whoa! Can I speak here?
What is this?

1001
01:13:11,082 --> 01:13:15,303
[Silva] And then
the military police came
to Carioca, searched his bag.

1002
01:13:15,391 --> 01:13:19,786
And then they said
he should be taken to jail

1003
01:13:19,873 --> 01:13:24,530
as a preventive arrestment,
to be searched and inquired.

1004
01:13:24,617 --> 01:13:29,666
[Carioca]
They're taking me away.
I don't have anything in my bag.

1005
01:13:29,753 --> 01:13:34,279
How this information
was being virilized
was really amazing.

1006
01:13:34,366 --> 01:13:36,803
Like sharing, sharing, sharing,
tweets, tweets, tweets,

1007
01:13:36,890 --> 01:13:38,239
mention, mention, mention.

1008
01:13:38,326 --> 01:13:39,937
"The Ninja is being arrested."

1009
01:13:40,024 --> 01:13:42,418
And suddenly there was,
like, a small crowd.

1010
01:13:42,505 --> 01:13:44,637
Like 5,000 people.

1011
01:13:44,724 --> 01:13:47,814
And all of them was
screaming together,

1012
01:13:47,901 --> 01:13:51,209
[in Portuguese]
"Hey, police,
where is the Midia Ninja?"

1013
01:13:51,296 --> 01:13:57,084
[chanting] Hey, police,
where is the Midia Ninja?

1014
01:13:57,171 --> 01:13:59,260
At the police station,

1015
01:13:59,347 --> 01:14:04,875
there were some lawyers
to help us, some activists.

1016
01:14:04,962 --> 01:14:06,442
That's where I met Bruno Teles.

1017
01:14:07,660 --> 01:14:09,053
[man speaking in Portuguese]

1018
01:14:11,751 --> 01:14:13,536
[woman speaking Portuguese]

1019
01:14:13,623 --> 01:14:16,321
-What's your name?
-My name is
Bruno Ferreira Teles.

1020
01:14:16,408 --> 01:14:20,194
[Teles]
The Midia Ninjas appeared
right when I needed to speak.

1021
01:14:20,281 --> 01:14:22,501
They gave me a voice.
They asked me if I wanted
to give them an interview.

1022
01:14:22,588 --> 01:14:25,722
I said I want to. I need to!

1023
01:14:25,809 --> 01:14:28,638
As we interviewed Bruno,

1024
01:14:28,725 --> 01:14:33,164
Globo broadcast that
he threw the Molotov

1025
01:14:33,251 --> 01:14:37,777
and had been arrested.

1026
01:14:37,864 --> 01:14:42,869
It was Bruno Ferreira
who was caught with a backpack
full of Molotov cocktails.

1027
01:14:42,956 --> 01:14:44,871
The police officer who was hit
with the Molotov cocktail

1028
01:14:44,958 --> 01:14:47,439
suffered burns to the thorax.

1029
01:14:50,355 --> 01:14:55,316
The big media in general
were all against me.

1030
01:14:55,403 --> 01:14:58,494
They associated me
with vandalism,
with violence.

1031
01:14:58,581 --> 01:14:59,973
[shouting]

1032
01:15:00,060 --> 01:15:04,282
I want to ask you
to help me to find the video

1033
01:15:04,369 --> 01:15:07,154
of the moment
where I ran from police.

1034
01:15:07,894 --> 01:15:10,331
They took me in,

1035
01:15:10,418 --> 01:15:12,986
and they are saying
I was there with bottles
of Molotov cocktails,

1036
01:15:13,073 --> 01:15:14,901
and I was not.

1037
01:15:14,988 --> 01:15:18,601
That's all I'm asking,
that you search out these videos
and collaborate.

1038
01:15:18,688 --> 01:15:21,734
[Silva, in English]
Then we posted this video from
the mobile, like, real time,

1039
01:15:21,821 --> 01:15:23,606
and it virilized very fast.

1040
01:15:28,132 --> 01:15:30,569
[Carioca, in Portuguese]
Our in-box exploded.

1041
01:15:30,656 --> 01:15:33,441
5,000 e-mails in 24 hours.

1042
01:15:33,529 --> 01:15:36,532
A ton of images and video

1043
01:15:36,619 --> 01:15:40,448
that showed Bruno's innocence.

1044
01:16:09,477 --> 01:16:10,348
[glass shattering]

1045
01:16:14,265 --> 01:16:16,354
[vocalizing]

1046
01:16:17,877 --> 01:16:19,531
[video sound distorted]

1047
01:16:28,540 --> 01:16:31,412
[vocalizing continues]

1048
01:16:34,764 --> 01:16:35,591
[glass shattering]

1049
01:17:02,922 --> 01:17:05,185
[woman] What is this, people?
This is surreal.

1050
01:17:05,925 --> 01:17:10,713
[woman vocalizing]

1051
01:17:20,113 --> 01:17:22,289
[vocalizing]

1052
01:17:25,379 --> 01:17:26,859
[shouting]

1053
01:17:38,392 --> 01:17:40,612
[music distorting]

1054
01:17:49,273 --> 01:17:50,666
[gunshot muffled]

1055
01:17:55,061 --> 01:17:56,584
[electrical crackling]

1056
01:18:04,201 --> 01:18:05,376
[crackling continues]

1057
01:18:16,822 --> 01:18:20,043
The video was just getting
bigger in the social media.

1058
01:18:20,130 --> 01:18:22,001
Bruno Teles became a character.

1059
01:18:22,088 --> 01:18:24,047
[crowd shouting]

1060
01:18:26,353 --> 01:18:31,707
Within a day,
Globo reversed their position.

1061
01:18:31,794 --> 01:18:35,145
They said I was a student,
a good kid.

1062
01:18:36,015 --> 01:18:40,150
Everyone likes him.

1063
01:18:40,237 --> 01:18:46,069
Contrary to information
released by the military
and civil police,

1064
01:18:46,156 --> 01:18:51,074
the student Bruno Teles
did not possess explosives
at the time of his arrest.

1065
01:18:51,161 --> 01:18:53,554
[Silva] They said
that Bruno was innocent,

1066
01:18:53,641 --> 01:18:58,168
and they used Midia Ninja image.

1067
01:18:58,255 --> 01:19:00,474
And they credited Midia Ninja.

1068
01:19:00,561 --> 01:19:03,913
It was the first
time that we were seeing

1069
01:19:04,000 --> 01:19:08,395
Globo recognizing
a free media collective

1070
01:19:08,482 --> 01:19:12,922
as a legitimate player
in the communication game.

1071
01:19:13,009 --> 01:19:15,707
It was a next step.

1072
01:19:17,361 --> 01:19:19,363
[crowd shouting]

1073
01:19:22,322 --> 01:19:23,410
[gunshot]

1074
01:19:28,546 --> 01:19:30,026
[explosion]

1075
01:19:42,038 --> 01:19:43,082
[glass shattering]

1076
01:19:46,738 --> 01:19:52,135
[woman]
Oh, he's changing his shirt.

1077
01:19:56,052 --> 01:19:57,575
[shouting]

1078
01:20:00,404 --> 01:20:03,407
[woman vocalizing]

1079
01:20:12,851 --> 01:20:15,854
[Orlando]
This is an old strategy.

1080
01:20:15,941 --> 01:20:20,816
When police infiltrate groups
and appear as activists,

1081
01:20:20,903 --> 01:20:23,819
they legitimize
the police violence.

1082
01:20:27,866 --> 01:20:29,563
[explosion]

1083
01:20:29,650 --> 01:20:33,524
For the population,
if the protestors
are launching explosions,

1084
01:20:33,611 --> 01:20:37,354
the police must do
whatever is necessary,
even on the margins of the law.

1085
01:20:37,441 --> 01:20:40,618
[Bentes]
The best form of security today

1086
01:20:40,705 --> 01:20:44,491
is to live stream everything.

1087
01:20:44,578 --> 01:20:49,235
If everyone knows where you are,
then you're safe.

1088
01:20:49,322 --> 01:20:54,893
The French word "surveillance"
implies watching from above.

1089
01:20:54,980 --> 01:20:57,722
In this case "sub-veillance"
is more accurate.

1090
01:20:57,809 --> 01:21:03,859
Bottom-up. The crowd
surveils from all angles.

1091
01:21:03,946 --> 01:21:09,299
[crowd chanting in Portuguese]
Hey, undercover cops,
go fuck yourself!

1092
01:21:12,345 --> 01:21:16,349
Are you an undercover cop?I'm a protestor, idiot!

1093
01:21:18,525 --> 01:21:20,788
[shouting continues]

1094
01:21:22,007 --> 01:21:23,226
[crowd booing]

1095
01:21:26,969 --> 01:21:33,540
It took only
the time for the video
to circulate online and on TV,

1096
01:21:33,627 --> 01:21:36,500
then habeas corpus was filed,
and he was released.

1097
01:21:37,457 --> 01:21:39,546
[woman] Bruno! Come here!

1098
01:21:42,462 --> 01:21:43,681
[woman crying]

1099
01:21:55,040 --> 01:21:56,607
[Orlando]
What if we didn't have
these images?

1100
01:21:56,694 --> 01:21:59,392
[shouting]

1101
01:21:59,479 --> 01:22:03,875
How many others
don't have the good fortune
of being filmed?

1102
01:22:05,485 --> 01:22:10,621
[crowd chanting]
Ninja! Ninja! Ninja!

1103
01:22:10,708 --> 01:22:12,928
Ten people are still inside,
some of them Ninjas.

1104
01:22:13,015 --> 01:22:17,715
[crowd repeating]

1105
01:22:17,802 --> 01:22:19,673
And we will not leave...

1106
01:22:19,760 --> 01:22:22,546
[crowd repeating]

1107
01:22:22,633 --> 01:22:24,852
...until they are all released.

1108
01:22:24,940 --> 01:22:26,767
[cheering]

1109
01:22:29,596 --> 01:22:30,510
[crowd] Ninja!

1110
01:22:33,557 --> 01:22:37,604
[crowd chanting]

1111
01:22:44,307 --> 01:22:47,440
[digital pop music playing]

1112
01:22:59,670 --> 01:23:03,152
I've always been a fan
of the terms "hacking"
and "hacktivism."

1113
01:23:03,239 --> 01:23:04,718
Especially "hacktivism"

1114
01:23:04,805 --> 01:23:08,200
which is the combination of
hacking and political activism.

1115
01:23:08,287 --> 01:23:13,031
And those combined
are pretty powerful to me.

1116
01:23:13,118 --> 01:23:17,775
It's about encouraging people
not to accept technology
at face value.

1117
01:23:19,255 --> 01:23:20,996
We need to encourage people
to think about

1118
01:23:21,083 --> 01:23:23,911
what it is that surrounds them,

1119
01:23:23,999 --> 01:23:26,305
to question authority

1120
01:23:26,392 --> 01:23:30,527
in a sense of the authority
being the technological
environment around them

1121
01:23:30,614 --> 01:23:35,967
and to realize that
when you start pulling back
the layers of all of this,

1122
01:23:36,054 --> 01:23:38,230
that's where
the exercise of power is.

1123
01:23:38,317 --> 01:23:41,538
So if we want liberal democracy
to flourish,

1124
01:23:41,625 --> 01:23:44,541
we need people
to start lifting back the layers

1125
01:23:44,628 --> 01:23:46,021
and understanding
what's going on.

1126
01:23:55,117 --> 01:23:58,946
[clicking]

1127
01:24:01,688 --> 01:24:05,562
[Snowden] I think ultimately
it comes down to understanding
what your values are,

1128
01:24:05,649 --> 01:24:08,173
because how do you
develop your thoughts, right?

1129
01:24:08,260 --> 01:24:10,262
How do you determine
what it is that
you truly believe?

1130
01:24:10,349 --> 01:24:13,700
How do you determine what
it is you really want to say,

1131
01:24:13,787 --> 01:24:15,833
if you can't even
keep notes safely?

1132
01:24:15,920 --> 01:24:19,924
If you can't
have some private space,
some space for thought,

1133
01:24:20,011 --> 01:24:22,753
some space to enjoy the product
of your own intellect,

1134
01:24:22,840 --> 01:24:25,277
to share that with people
close to you who you trust.

1135
01:24:25,364 --> 01:24:28,063
Whether they're family,
whether they're colleagues,
whether they're compatriots.

1136
01:24:37,159 --> 01:24:42,512
[Deibert] One thing
that I see a lot is, this idea
of technology as a solution.

1137
01:24:42,599 --> 01:24:45,123
It's a natural thing.
Okay, technology
is under threat.

1138
01:24:45,210 --> 01:24:47,082
Let's find
a technological solution.

1139
01:24:48,605 --> 01:24:50,302
There are so many projects now

1140
01:24:50,389 --> 01:24:54,219
around secure communications,
platforms, chats,
instant messaging.

1141
01:24:54,306 --> 01:24:58,354
But it's only one component
of a solution set.

1142
01:24:58,441 --> 01:25:02,401
And I think often overlooked
are the legal and political
dimensions.

1143
01:25:03,620 --> 01:25:04,708
If we're talking about

1144
01:25:04,795 --> 01:25:06,884
protecting and preserving
all of this,

1145
01:25:06,971 --> 01:25:10,931
as a secure and open
communication space,

1146
01:25:11,018 --> 01:25:12,846
that means holding governments
accountable.

1147
01:25:12,933 --> 01:25:14,892
It means holding
companies accountable.

1148
01:25:14,979 --> 01:25:17,416
Putting in place rules and laws

1149
01:25:17,503 --> 01:25:22,465
that ensures they can't
do things that infringe
on our freedoms and rights.

1150
01:25:22,552 --> 01:25:25,642
That to me is, uh,

1151
01:25:25,729 --> 01:25:29,733
such a critical foundation
of a digital democracy today.

